Title : B. G. Plumer
Text : '''Bradbury Greenleaf "B. G" Plumer''' (May 22, 1830 &ndash; July 22, 1886) was an American businessman, farmer, and politician.

Born in [[Epping, New Hampshire]], Plumer took part in the [[California Gold Rush]]. He then moved to [[Saint Louis, Missouri]]. In 1854, Plumer moved to [[Wausau, Wisconsin]] and was involved in the lumber business. Plumer also farmed and raised cattle. In 1866, Plumer served in the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]]. His brother was [[Daniel L. Plumer]], who also served in the Wisconsin State Assembly. He committed suicide with a firearm in Wausau, Wisconsin.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.marathoncountyhistory.org/PeopleDetails.php?PeopleId=470 |title=Marathon County Historical Society-B.G. Plumer |access-date=2014-04-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427045642/http://www.marathoncountyhistory.org/PeopleDetails.php?PeopleId=470 |archive-date=2014-04-27 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>'History of Marathon County, Wisconsin and Representative Citizens,' Louis Marchetti, Richmond-Arnold Publishing Company, Chicago, Illinois: 1913, Biographical Sketch of Bradbury Greenleaf Plumer, pg. 598-599</ref>

